A quadratic programming algorithm to minimize Eq. 4 originally proposed by [13] alternates between updating 𝐆𝐆{\mathbf{G}}bold_G and 𝐒𝐒{\mathbf{S}}bold_S. The source matrix 𝐆𝐆{\mathbf{G}}bold_G is updated using an elastic net estimate, while 𝐒𝐒{\mathbf{S}}bold_S is given by a Procrustes rotation through the singular value decomposition (SVD) to ensure orthogonal columns in 𝐒𝐒{\mathbf{S}}bold_S:

We leverage the PyTorch stochastic optimization framework and the Adam optimizer [14] to minimize Eq. 4. PyTorch has an efficient automatic numerical gradient computational structure, which only requires specifying a loss function and the parameters to be learned. To avoid gradient explosions due to the non-differentiable l1subscript𝑙1l_{1}italic_l start_POSTSUBSCRIPT 1 end_POSTSUBSCRIPT-regularization term in SPCA, we introduce two non-negative matrices 𝐆=𝐆p−𝐆n𝐆subscript𝐆𝑝subscript𝐆𝑛{\mathbf{G}}={\mathbf{G}}_{p}-{\mathbf{G}}_{n}bold_G = bold_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_p end_POSTSUBSCRIPT - bold_G start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_n end_POSTSUBSCRIPT. For archetypal analysis, both 𝐆𝐆{\mathbf{G}}bold_G and 𝐒𝐒{\mathbf{S}}bold_S are learned, and the non-negativity and sum-to-one constraints are implemented through the softmax function. Though archetypal analysis uses the same loss function as SPCA (without regularization terms), the directional variant is different and may be found in [11]. We used a learning rate of 0.010.010.010.01.
